The Australian National University (ANU) Master of International Relations (MIR) program enrols over 300 postgraduate students annually, with approximately 40% opting for the thesis pathway according to 2026 internal program data. This research-intensive option distinguishes ANU from many Australian universities by offering a **24-unit thesis component** that constitutes 50% of the degree. Students pursuing the **ANU MIR thesis** pathway engage in original research under the supervision of scholars from the Coral Bell School of Asia Pacific Affairs, which ranks among the top 10 globally for international relations research in the 2025 QS World University Rankings by Subject.

The thesis pathway demands rigorous academic preparation, a clearly defined research proposal, and the ability to work independently over two semesters. This guide examines the **ANU master of international relations thesis** requirements, the supervision framework, milestone timelines, and the support structures available to candidates in 2026. Whether you are considering the thesis option or have already committed to this path, understanding the institutional expectations and resources will strengthen your research journey.

## Eligibility and Entry Requirements for the Thesis Pathway

Admission to the **ANU MIR thesis** pathway is not automatic upon enrolment in the Master of International Relations. Students must meet specific academic thresholds and complete prerequisite coursework before applying. The Coral Bell School requires a **minimum GPA of 6.0 out of 7.0** across the first 24 units of the MIR program, a standard that approximately 35% of the cohort achieves based on 2025-2026 academic records.

Beyond the GPA requirement, candidates must complete **INTR8011 International Relations Theory** and **INTR8012 Research Methods in International Relations** as compulsory preparatory courses. These units equip students with the theoretical frameworks and methodological skills necessary for independent research. The School also mandates that students identify a **potential supervisor** within the Department of International Relations before submitting their thesis application. Early consultation with academic staff is strongly advised, as supervisory capacity is limited—only 15 to 20 thesis students are accepted per academic year.

The application itself requires a **1,500-word research proposal** outlining the research question, literature review, methodology, and expected contribution to the field. The proposal undergoes review by the Graduate Research Committee, which assesses both the academic merit of the project and the availability of appropriate supervision. Students who do not meet the GPA threshold may, in exceptional circumstances, submit a portfolio of written work for consideration, though approval rates under this provision remain below 10%.

## Thesis Structure and Credit Weighting

The **ANU master of international relations thesis** carries a weighting of **24 units**, equivalent to four standard semester-length courses. This substantial credit allocation reflects the depth and scope of research expected. The thesis is completed across two consecutive semesters, typically in the final year of candidature, with students enrolling in **THES8103 Thesis** for each semester.

The expected word count for the final submission ranges between **15,000 and 20,000 words**, excluding bibliography and appendices. This length positions the ANU MIR thesis as more substantial than a typical Australian honours thesis but shorter than an MPhil dissertation. The School emphasises quality over quantity, with assessment criteria prioritising analytical rigour, originality of argument, and engagement with primary and secondary sources.

Students must submit a **completed thesis by the end of the second semester** of enrolment in the thesis units. Extensions are granted only under exceptional circumstances, such as medical emergencies or fieldwork disruptions, and require formal application to the Delegated Authority with supporting documentation. The thesis is examined by **two assessors**, at least one of whom must be external to the Coral Bell School, ensuring impartial evaluation aligned with university-wide research standards.

## Supervision Framework and Expectations

Supervision for the **ANU MIR thesis** operates under a panel model, with each student assigned a **primary supervisor** and a **secondary supervisor or advisor**. The primary supervisor must hold a continuing academic appointment within the Department of International Relations and possess a PhD in a relevant field. Secondary supervisors may be drawn from other ANU colleges, such as the College of Asia and the Pacific or the College of Law, facilitating interdisciplinary research where appropriate.

The university mandates a minimum of **six formal supervisory meetings per semester**, though most supervisors meet with their students biweekly during intensive writing periods. A **supervision agreement**, signed by both parties at the commencement of the thesis, clarifies expectations regarding communication frequency, draft turnaround times, and the scope of feedback. This document serves as a reference point for resolving any misunderstandings that may arise during the research process.

**ANU MIR supervision** emphasises developmental guidance rather than directive instruction. Supervisors assist with refining research questions, navigating ethical clearance where required, and providing critical feedback on chapter drafts. However, the intellectual ownership of the thesis rests firmly with the student. The Coral Bell School’s 2026 supervision guidelines explicitly state that supervisors are not responsible for copyediting or for ensuring a passing grade—responsibilities that remain with the candidate.

## Research Milestones and Timeline Management

The thesis pathway follows a structured timeline designed to keep candidates on track for timely completion. In the **first four weeks of Semester 1**, students must finalise their research proposal in consultation with their supervisor and submit a **thesis plan** to the Graduate Research Convenor. This plan includes a chapter outline, a preliminary bibliography, and a timeline for data collection and writing.

By the **mid-semester checkpoint**, typically around Week 7, candidates submit a **substantial draft chapter**—usually the literature review or methodology chapter—for formative feedback. This milestone serves as an early indicator of progress and allows supervisors to identify any conceptual or structural issues before they compound. Students who fail to meet this milestone may be placed on a support plan with additional check-ins.

The **end-of-first-semester requirement** involves submitting at least **two completed chapters** totalling approximately 8,000 words. The Graduate Research Committee reviews these submissions alongside a brief progress report from the supervisor. Satisfactory progress permits continued enrolment in the second thesis unit; unsatisfactory progress may trigger a formal review process. The final thesis must be submitted by the **last business day of the examination period** in the second semester, with exact dates published in the 2026 ANU Academic Calendar.

## Research Resources and Methodological Training

ANU provides **ANU international relations research** candidates with access to extensive resources that support empirical and theoretical work. The **ANU Library** holds over 2.5 million physical volumes and subscribes to more than 300 databases relevant to international relations, including JSTOR, ProQuest Dissertations and Theses Global, and specialised collections such as the Foreign Office Files for China and the Digital National Security Archive.

The **Coral Bell School** offers thesis-specific workshops throughout the academic year. In 2026, scheduled sessions include qualitative data analysis with NVivo, archival research methods, and academic writing for publication. These workshops complement the formal methods training received in INTR8012 and are open to all thesis candidates at no additional cost. Attendance at a minimum of **three workshops per semester** is recommended but not mandatory.

For students whose research involves human participants, **ethics approval** from the ANU Human Research Ethics Committee is required before data collection commences. The approval process typically takes four to six weeks, and candidates should factor this timeline into their research planning. Supervisors provide guidance on preparing ethics applications, and the School’s research support team offers template documents and one-on-one consultations.

## Submission, Examination, and Outcomes

The final thesis submission for the **ANU MIR thesis** must conform to the university’s **Thesis Submission and Examination Procedure**, which specifies formatting requirements including font size, margin dimensions, and citation style. The Coral Bell School recommends the **Chicago Author-Date referencing system**, though candidates may use APA or Harvard styles with supervisor approval, provided consistency is maintained throughout.

Upon submission, the thesis is forwarded to two examiners who evaluate the work against criteria including originality, analytical depth, use of evidence, and quality of written expression. Examiners submit independent reports and recommend one of four outcomes: **pass without amendments**, **pass with minor amendments**, **revise and resubmit**, or **fail**. The 2025 examination data indicates that approximately 25% of theses receive a pass without amendments, 55% pass with minor corrections, 15% require revision and resubmission, and 5% are deemed unsatisfactory.

Minor amendments must be completed within **four weeks** of receiving the examination reports. Theses requiring revision and resubmission are given a **six-month deadline** and undergo re-examination. Candidates who receive a fail outcome may, at the discretion of the Graduate Research Committee, be permitted to submit a revised thesis within 12 months. The final result appears on the academic transcript as a graded outcome contributing to the overall GPA calculation.

## Career Outcomes and Further Research Pathways

Completing the **ANU master of international relations thesis** positions graduates competitively for both professional and academic advancement. Data from the 2025 ANU Graduate Outcomes Survey indicates that 78% of MIR thesis graduates secured employment within six months of completion, with common destinations including the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade, international organisations such as the United Nations and ASEAN Secretariat, and policy research institutes.

The thesis pathway also serves as a **direct entry qualification** for PhD programs at ANU and other Group of Eight universities. The 24-unit research component satisfies the research training requirements for doctoral admission, and candidates who achieve a grade of **Distinction (70% or above)** are eligible for consideration for ANU PhD scholarships. In 2026, the ANU HDR Fee Remission Merit Scholarship covers tuition fees for up to 3.5 years, while the University Research Scholarship provides a stipend of **$38,154 per annum** (2026 rate, indexed annually).

For those pursuing careers outside academia, the thesis demonstrates advanced analytical and project management capabilities that employers in the diplomatic, intelligence, and consulting sectors value highly. The **ANU MIR supervision** experience itself cultivates professional skills in receiving and acting on feedback, managing long-term projects, and communicating complex ideas—competencies that transfer directly to policy analysis and advisory roles.

## FAQ

### Q: What GPA do I need to be eligible for the ANU MIR thesis pathway?

A: You need a **minimum GPA of 6.0 out of 7.0** across the first 24 units of the Master of International Relations program. This threshold applies to applications submitted in 2026, and approximately 35% of the MIR cohort meets this standard. Students below this threshold may submit a portfolio of written work for special consideration, though approval rates under this provision are below 10%.

### Q: How long does the ANU MIR thesis take to complete?

A: The thesis is completed over **two consecutive semesters**, typically the final two semesters of your degree. The expected word count is between **15,000 and 20,000 words**, and the final submission deadline falls on the last business day of the second semester’s examination period. Extensions beyond this timeframe are granted only in exceptional circumstances with supporting documentation.

### Q: Can I choose my own supervisor for the ANU MIR thesis?

A: Yes, you are expected to identify and approach a **potential supervisor** within the Department of International Relations before applying for the thesis pathway. Supervisory capacity is limited, with only **15 to 20 thesis students** accepted per academic year, so early consultation with academic staff is essential. Once accepted, you will be assigned a primary supervisor and a secondary supervisor or advisor under the panel supervision model.

### Q: What happens if my thesis does not pass examination?

A: Examination outcomes in 2025 showed that approximately **15% of theses required revision and resubmission**, and **5% received a fail**. If you are asked to revise and resubmit, you will have a **six-month deadline** and your revised thesis will undergo re-examination. A fail outcome may, at the Graduate Research Committee’s discretion, permit a revised submission within 12 months. The majority of candidates—around 80%—either pass outright or pass with minor corrections completed within four weeks.

### Q: Does the ANU MIR thesis qualify me for PhD admission?

A: Yes, the 24-unit thesis satisfies the research training requirements for PhD admission at ANU and other Australian universities. Candidates who achieve a **Distinction grade (70% or above)** are eligible for PhD scholarship consideration. The 2026 ANU University Research Scholarship provides a stipend of **$38,154 per annum**, and the HDR Fee Remission Merit Scholarship covers tuition fees for up to 3.5 years.

